Note: ========================================
Note: x86-64 Assembly Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for x86-64 assembly translation
Note: Test Coverage: Lexer, Parser, Translation, Generation, Round-trip
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/x86/hir_to_x86.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the x86-64 assembly translator. Runs lexer,
parser, to-HIR, from-HIR, and round-trip checks in dependency order
so failures point at the lowest-level component.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Failures are reported
inline by assert_* helpers.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 12 tests print "[OK]" lines -> clean suite
- Any assert_* failure prints "FAILED:" line -> visible in CI output
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_x86_tests":
    proc print_string with "x86-64 Assembly Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline
    proc print_newline
    proc test_lexer_basic
    proc test_lexer_instructions
    proc test_lexer_registers
    proc test_lexer_numbers
    proc test_lexer_directives
    proc test_parser_instruction
    proc test_parser_label
    proc test_parser_directive
    proc test_parser_memory
    proc test_x86_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_x86
    proc test_round_trip
    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All x86-64 assembly tests completed!"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Smoke test for the x86-64 lexer: tokenize AT&T-syntax "mov %rax,
%rbx" and assert at least one token comes out. Minimal because more
specific assertions are in the per-category tests.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create source, lex, tokenize, read tokens from offset 24, assert
size > 0, destroy lexer.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "mov %rax, %rbx" -> > 0 tokens
- Lexer fails on "%" prefix -> count == 0 -> "Basic tokenization produces tokens" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_basic":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 lexer (basic)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov %rax, %rbx"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens
    Let _basic_ok be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _basic_ok, "Basic tokenization produces tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Basic lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer recognizes 8 common x86-64 instruction mnemonics
(mov, add, sub, push, pop, call, ret, jmp). Catches a regression
where an alias table update missed one of these core instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "mov add sub push pop call ret jmp", assert count == 8,
then loop and assert each token type == 1 (INSTRUCTION).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 8 mnemonics -> INSTRUCTION (type 1), passed
- "ret" misclassified as identifier -> "Token is INSTRUCTION" fails
- Count != 8 -> "Instruction tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_instructions":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 lexer (instructions)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov add sub push pop call ret jmp"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 8 instruction tokens
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 8, "Instruction tokenization"

    Note: Verify all are instruction tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than token_count:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        proc assert_equals with token_type, 1, "Token is INSTRUCTION"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Instruction lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies AT&T-syntax register tokenization. Each "%name" produces
two tokens (% sentinel + identifier) by current lexer design, so
"%rax %rbx %rcx %rdx" yields exactly 8 tokens. Catches a regression
where the "%" is consumed as part of the identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "%rax %rbx %rcx %rdx", assert count == 8.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- 4 registers -> 8 tokens (% + name pairs), passed
- Lexer fuses "%rax" into one token -> count == 4 -> "Register tokenization" fails
- Lexer fails on "%" -> count drops
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_registers":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 lexer (registers)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "%rax %rbx %rcx %rdx"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 8 tokens (4 percent signs + 4 identifiers)
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 8, "Register tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Register lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies AT&T-style immediate numbers: $-prefixed decimal ($42),
hex ($0xFF), negative ($-17), and bare decimal (16). The "$"
prefix marks immediates in AT&T syntax (unlike Intel's bare numbers).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "$42 $0xFF $-17 16", assert count > 0 (split or fused
forms both valid).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- 4 number forms -> > 0 tokens
- Lexer rejects hex 0xFF -> count drops or 0 -> "Number tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_numbers":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 lexer (numbers)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "$42 $0xFF $-17 16"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have tokens for each number (with $ prefix tokens)
    Let _num_ok be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _num_ok, "Number tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Number lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies GNU-as directive tokenization: .text, .data, .globl,
.section. Directives have type 3 to distinguish from instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize ".text .data .globl .section", assert count == 4, loop
and assert each token type == 3 (DIRECTIVE).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 4 directives -> DIRECTIVE (type 3), passed
- Lexer drops "." -> may classify as INSTRUCTION -> fails
- Count != 4 -> "Directive tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_directives":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 lexer (directives)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with ".text .data .globl .section"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 4 directive tokens
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 4, "Directive tokenization"

    Note: Verify all are directive tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 4:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        proc assert_equals with token_type, 3, "Token is DIRECTIVE"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Directive lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser builds an AST for an instruction with immediate
source and register destination ("mov $42, %rax"). Asserts the
operand children list is non-empty so a bare-instruction regression
is caught.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "mov $42, %rax", parse -> ast. Assert ast not null AND
children list at offset 24 has size > 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "mov $42, %rax" -> non-null AST with operands, passed
- Parser returns null -> "Instruction parsed" fails
- Parser drops operands -> "Instruction has operands" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_instruction":
    proc print_string with "Testing x86 parser (instruction)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov $42, %rax"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Instruction parsed"

    Note: Verify AST has children
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let _child_ok be child_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _child_ok, "Instruction has operands"

    proc destroy_asm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Instruction parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a bare label ("main:"). Catches a
regression where the parser requires content after the colon.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "main:", parse -> ast. Assert ast not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "main:" -> non-null label AST, passed
- Parser rejects bare label -> ast == 0 -> "Label parsed" fails
@End TestCases

